  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering carries serious criminal penalties. Typically, these can include:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences\n- Up to 10-20 years imprisonment per offense\n- Potential longer sentences for multiple or aggravated charges\n\n2. Financial penalties\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n\n3. Asset forfeiture\n- Government can seize assets connected to laundering activities\n\n4. Additional consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific federal statute violated\n- Whether the laundering involved other criminal activities\n- Individual's criminal history\n\nProsecution typically occurs under statutes like:\n- Bank Secrecy Act\n- Money Laundering Control Act\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n\nExact penalties can vary based on specific circumstances and federal prosecutorial discretion.",
